#: ../../source/example_gallery/basics.rst:100 a9dda4c3f2424a5cae979117ef0e9529
msgid ""
"``examples/basics/basis_fn.py`` plots the polynomial shape functions "
"themselves. For 1D elements they appear as curves on :math:`[-1,1]`; for "
"2D elements as 3D surfaces on the reference triangle or square; for 3D "
"elements one figure per order with a slice through the volume."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/basics.rst:106 65f36582f43046c68321c76b9a3a29f9
msgid ""
"The script uses ``element.get_basis_fns(order)``, the same call "
":class:`~tensormesh.ElementAssembler` makes during assembly. If a shape "
"function looks wrong here, it is wrong in your assembled matrix too."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/basics.rst:111 4ccfb55de7884ec597c53c39c8ccf0aa
msgid ""
"In principle ``get_basis_fns`` accepts **arbitrary** polynomial order — "
"there is no hard cap baked into the API. The figures below show 1D and 2D"
" shape functions at orders 1–3 (plus the full composite view) and 3D "
"shape functions at order 1; higher 3D orders are equally available, they "
"are simply omitted here for space."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/basics.rst:120 ab186ccd23164cad8270e540d353d19f
msgid ""
"Although arbitrary orders are supported, very high orders (in practice "
":math:`\\geq 4` for some element classes) are evaluated through a "
"Vandermonde matrix that becomes increasingly ill-conditioned with order. "
"The script may print a numerical warning in that regime. The returned "
"values are still usable — but if you see those warnings during a real "
"solve, drop to a lower order or switch to a different element class. For "
"most FEM workloads orders 1–3 are the sweet spot."
msgstr ""

