#: ../../source/example_gallery/basics.rst:195 5d76a3f5bb0c467390f9e6d43059b028
msgid "Gmsh / VTK ↔ TensorMesh node ordering"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/basics.rst:197 e1515a0d3b6b44dc8e10cf64aea718ff
msgid ""
"``examples/basics/element_gallery.py`` puts TensorMesh's internal node "
"numbering side-by-side with the Gmsh / VTK convention, for 2D and 3D "
"elements at orders 2–4. The output is a two-row plot per element type: "
"top row is the TensorMesh / FEniCS-style ordering; bottom row is the Gmsh"
" / VTK ordering."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/example_gallery/basics.rst:203 4710a902ff3f408b88275fd97559d772
msgid ""
"This is the visual companion to the ``reorder=True`` story in "
":doc:`../user_guide/meshes`: when you load a Gmsh ``.msh`` or write a VTU"
" through meshio, TensorMesh applies the inverse permutation returned by "
"``element.get_gmsh_permutation(order)`` so internal connectivity always "
"uses the same convention. If you ever question which numbering a "
"particular array is in, this script makes it obvious."
msgstr ""

